I tried to put the items into logical order. We'll start with managing, which includes multiple processes. From this we'll probably look at what should be incorporated into the workflow.

On new vendor requests: we discussed the details and an automated notification was triggered — Awa 6A Wax, I think — which I saw. Essentially, vendor onboarding is what you did yesterday. Consolidating vendor onboarding is the point: it's happening in many places today. For onboarding a new supplier, we actually get an automated feed through 3E. We need to understand how a new vendor payee is created and how it fits into the P2P procurement process.

Currently, someone raises a request to add or update a vendor in a spreadsheet, which sends a request into 3E for review. There is an automatic notification email that comes through; no one manually enters that notification. New vendor payees are discovered through invoices we receive — we don't always know about a new payee until an invoice arrives and we process it. So, in practice, business users don't often directly create vendor payees; it's triggered by activity, usually receiving an invoice and asking us to process it through our P2P workflow.

In the scenario where an invoice needs payment and a new vendor creation is required, you would create a task for different team members. Creating a vendor payee is effectively a sub-process, which is why we have two separate process maps — it's an exception to the main flow, so we've separated it.

The trigger most of the time is invoice receipt. Should vendor creation be a subtask of the managing invoice service? Possibly — it may be better as a subtask within the manage-invoice workflow. Requests can be specific and span different categories, so we need the possibility to categorize them, which will help us measure how many vendor creations we perform and the impact on invoice processing.

Categorization matters for internal tracking even if it doesn't affect the external process. Even simple metrics like number of invoices split or moved would be useful. However, a ticket can only be assigned to one category, and invoices are subject to different processes, so we can't capture everything in one ticket right now.

ServiceNow can auto-assign tickets based on thresholds and categories, which is helpful. There are two main options to get a new vendor into the process: 1) a new invoice comes in, which triggers the vendor intake; or 2) someone within the firm proactively requests to add a vendor through the P2P process. The latter is the proactive workflow that avoids the reactive onboarding when an invoice arrives.

Proactive vendor onboarding saves time and reduces failure demand because external parties — partners and those outside AP — don't always get it right. If they did, we'd see less reactive work downstream. So capturing the automated P2P emails is important.

The team asked: is the P2P automated email captured in Cherwell? Those automated emails come into Cherwell from various sources. The subject line for new vendor payee requests is consistent and identifiable, which makes them easy to detect. We could trigger a task from that notification. We need to explore the level of feeds and whether they can show the level of failure demand, so we can incentivize the communities to do vendor onboarding correctly upfront.

