Required invoice fields: legal name, tax number, bank details, company number — we generally cannot accept an invoice that isn't valid or missing tax invoice details. Compliance checks are done by other teams outside AP in most cases. For new suppliers over £10,000, additional checks are done.

Approvals: the vendor onboarding in 3E has thresholds that trigger additional authorization. You input details and a workflow for authorization kicks off; the workflow seems to support the check and sign-off functions.

We can provide dashboards that show how many vendors are being added, SLA breaches, and approvals. It will help to have drill-down on vendors over certain thresholds and approval history (who approved what). Country-specific certificates and reporting can be part of that.

In invoice processing, if an invoice is wrong we may put it on hold rather than reject it outright. A "hold" state with reasons is better. Workflow should allow returning invoices to suppliers to provide missing info like bank details before processing continues. We should incorporate a pre-checklist into the vendor intake workflow to avoid repetitive manual checks. Mandatory fields and attachments should be enforced so you cannot progress without required documentation and evidence. There should be a "callback" field and timestamps for all interactions to create an audit trail that you can report on (e.g., how long did vendor onboarding take?).

In 3E, there are some controls such as checking ABN uniqueness in Australia. The ABN is a unique identifier and 3E will flag duplicates, but it’s not a hard stop: users can still submit. We should talk to the 3E team about preventing duplicate entries and improving upstream validation to reduce failure demand downstream.

We need to separate value demand (work that adds value) from failure demand (work caused by errors or omissions). Tasks record time and effort, and if we structure tasks so they stop the clock on waiting, we can capture the real effort and demonstrate failure demand data to influence the business.

Think ahead about how vendor pay will look when the new P2P system is live in a few months. If processes change in 2026/2027, we must update ServiceNow to reflect the new flows.

For higher-value invoices (for example, over £10,000), we should include a field in the workflow to record authentication of bank details and the person who verified them, including a timestamp and supporting evidence. This must be auditable in 3E and ServiceNow. Australia might use AUD 15,000 as a threshold in practice for additional checks.

Regarding subscription portals and vendor-managed services: some of these are managed in procurement as subscriptions rather than one-off vendors; treat them accordingly.

When an invoice is rejected, that should move the invoice to a "hold" state with documented reasons and tasks for further information. When the supplier supplies the missing data (e.g., bank details), the invoice should then return into the workflow for approval and payment. That continuation must be tracked.

SLA guidance: invoices that need to be paid immediately (urgent) are prioritised; vendor creation is often done ASAP to allow payment. Prioritization can be based on due date or urgency. There may be VIP invoices or ones with legal deadlines that need to be prioritized. The manager can set priorities and the dashboards can surface urgent items.

We’ll come back to the fields we need on invoice steps, but we must capture name, legal name, tax ID, bank details, and required supporting evidence as mandatory items. Use checklists in the workflow to ensure these checks happen once and are auditable.

Now moving to corporate cards:

We need to consolidate corporate card processes. There are many related workflows: new card applications, queries (pin numbers, troubleshooting), joiners/movers/leavers, cancellations, secondments, limits and approvals, reconciliation, and deductions. Corporate card requests currently start with an email to AP where requesters provide a business case, manager details, and reason. The form should capture estimated monthly spend and requested credit limit.

We should implement a matrix of eligibility and limits by role (partners, managers, operations) so some roles are pre-approved while others require further approval. Partners in Australia are typically given automatic eligibility at onboarding. In the UK, rules are similar but approvals have recently moved to a new setup with defined approvers. We need to align matrices globally, allow local variations, and ensure the workflow routes to the correct approver.

The bank (Amex/Westpac) sometimes rejects applications due to KYC issues. We are not directly responsible for the bank's KYC process but the workflow should capture the status changes, including when an application is awaiting bank action. Currently the team is unaware when the bank is processing it. ServiceNow can reflect external statuses: awaiting approval, sent to bank, pending bank response, on hold, rejected, etc. That will improve metrics and allow AP to follow up proactively.

Amex and other card providers may require personal identification documents (passport, driving license) and correct name/marital name details. If the applicant completes applications online with the correct supporting evidence, approvals and bank processing should be smoother. Provide guidance (knowledge articles) explaining the process, expected timelines, and required documents — host forms on the intranet and link to them in the ServiceNow workflow rather than storing them in ServiceNow as documents.

When the applicant completes the bank application and returns evidence, we get notification and can check it before submission. Once approved and the card is issued, we arrange card delivery or pick-up — sometimes cards are couriered to regional offices. The card is not active until the bank has completed their checks; this should be tracked within the workflow.

For global consistency, the card application forms in the UK and Australia should be aligned and attached or linked from the ServiceNow task. For the US, their forms might be different; we need to incorporate them when Amex releases them.

Joiners, movers, and leavers: we should integrate card management with HR events. When a leaver or secondment is recorded, that should trigger tasks to cancel or suspend cards, reduce limits, or set effective end dates. Some secondments are short-term and will need temporary adjustments rather than full cancellations. Notifications and dashboard views that surface upcoming secondments or leave-related actions will help avoid leaving cards active unnecessarily. Avoid relying on manual monthly lists; integrate the triggers so tasks are created automatically.

Cancellation scenarios: sometimes we reduce a card limit instead of cancelling (suspension) — we should formalize the cancellation and suspension processes with defined parameters. There are also dormant cards (unused for six to 12 months) that could be cancelled to reduce costs; build a report/dashboard to identify and action these.

We must consider whether to treat cards as assets assigned to individuals for better visibility and governance. There are data protection and PCI considerations if we store card data in ServiceNow, so check compliance before capturing sensitive card data.

Reconciliation and salary deductions: there are monthly reconciliation processes for Amex and other cards. In Australia, reconciliation and payroll deductions may be processed fortnightly, while the UK does it monthly. The reconciliation process typically extracts data from 3E or the expense management system and sends reconciled items to payroll for deductions. This process should be formalized: generate scheduled tasks to reconcile, track exceptions, and capture adjustments as tasks so they’re auditable and can inform behaviour change.

Expense management and corporate card spend: some users prefer to get reimbursed rather than have a corporate card. We should use policy and data to influence usage behaviour. We can flag low-value card requests and redirect to alternatives like subscriptions or department budgets.

Cash cards and department cards: AP manages cash cards used for events or temporary needs. These are loaded with funds and topped up as required. Issue, receipt handling, statements, and reconciliation are weekly activities. Department cards are typically assigned 1:1, but sometimes shared, which complicates reconciliation. The same reconciliation pattern applies: statements are sent to cardholders for receipts and approvals, then processed for direct debits.

